plot_title: Sales Performance of Devices Sold in the Store
user_query:
I want to know the sales performance of the devices sold in the store. 
User Feedback: I do not like the color of the plot Sales Performance of Devices Sold in the Store. Please fix it.
plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product: pd.DataFrame, sales_of_product: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    # Merge the sales data with product data to get unit_price
    merged_data = sales_of_product.merge(product, on='product_id')
    
    # Grouping the data by product and aggregating the total sales
    sales_summary = merged_data.groupby('product_name').agg(
        total_sales=pd.NamedAgg(column='quantity', aggfunc='sum'),
        total_revenue=pd.NamedAgg(column='quantity', aggfunc=lambda x: (x * merged_data.loc[x.index, 'unit_price']).sum())
    ).reset_index()
    
    # Creating the bar plot for sales performance with updated color
    fig = px.bar(sales_summary, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y=['total_sales', 'total_revenue'], 
                 title='Sales Performance of Devices Sold in the Store',
                 labels={'value': 'Amount', 'product_name': 'Product'},
                 color_discrete_sequence=['royalblue', 'orange'],  # Updated colors
                 barmode='group')
    
    return fig.to_json()

user_query:
I want to know the performance of the stock in 2015. 
User Feedback: Can you only include closing and opening price of the plot Stock Performance in 2015
plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.graph_objects as go

def code_generation_llm(Stock_Cluster):
    # Convert the 'Date' column to datetime
    Stock_Cluster['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(Stock_Cluster['Date'])
    
    # Filter the data for the year 2015
    data_2015 = Stock_Cluster[Stock_Cluster['Date'].dt.year == 2015]
    
    # Create a plotly figure for the stock performance in 2015
    fig = go.Figure()
    
    # Add traces for Open and Close prices only
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=data_2015['Date'], y=data_2015['Open'], mode='lines', name='Open', line=dict(color='blue')))
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=data_2015['Date'], y=data_2015['Close'], mode='lines', name='Close', line=dict(color='orange')))
    
    # Update layout
    fig.update_layout(title='Stock Performance in 2015',
                      xaxis_title='Date',
                      yaxis_title='Stock Price',
                      legend_title='Price Type',
                      template='plotly_white')
    
    # Return the figure in JSON format
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(googleplaystore):
    # Convert the relevant columns to appropriate data types
    googleplaystore['Installs'] = googleplaystore['Installs'].str.replace('+', '').str.replace(',', '').astype(int)
    googleplaystore['Reviews'] = googleplaystore['Reviews'].astype(int)
    googleplaystore['Rating'] = googleplaystore['Rating'].astype(float)
    
    # Create a scatter plot of Ratings vs. Number of Installs
    fig = px.scatter(googleplaystore, x='Installs', y='Rating',
                     title='Rating vs. Number of Installs',
                     labels={'Installs': 'Number of Installs', 'Rating': 'App Rating'},
                     hover_name='App', 
                     color='Category',
                     size='Reviews',
                     size_max=20)

    return fig.to_json()

plot_title: App Ratings vs Reviews in Google Play Store
user_query: The plot you created, App Ratings vs Reviews in Google Play Store, is very difficult to read. Can you modify it?
plot_code:
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(googleplaystore):
    # Creating a scatter plot for App Ratings vs Reviews
    fig = px.scatter(googleplaystore, 
                     x='Reviews', 
                     y='Rating', 
                     color='Category', 
                     title='App Ratings vs Reviews in Google Play Store',
                     labels={'Reviews': 'Number of Reviews', 'Rating': 'App Rating'},
                     hover_name='App',
                     size='Reviews', 
                     size_max=15,
                     opacity=0.7)

    # Updating layout for better readability
    fig.update_layout(
        xaxis_title='Number of Reviews',
        yaxis_title='App Rating',
        showlegend=True,
        legend_title='Category',
        font=dict(size=12),
        margin=dict(l=40, r=40, t=40, b=40)
    )
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Create a bar plot for products and their prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in the Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'},
                 text='unit_price')
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2f}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(yaxis=dict(title='Unit Price ($)', tickprefix="$"), 
                      xaxis_title='Product Name',
                      plot_bgcolor='rgba(0,0,0,0)',
                      template='plotly_white')
    return fig.to_json()

import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price (USD)'},
                 color='unit_price',
                 text='unit_price')
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text}$', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(uniformtext_minsize=8, uniformtext_mode='hide')
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Creating a bar plot for product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'},
                 color='unit_price',
                 text='unit_price')

    # Updating the layout for better readability
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(yaxis_title='Unit Price ($)', xaxis_title='Product Name', xaxis_tickangle=-45)
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Create a bar plot for product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'},
                 color='unit_price', 
                 text='unit_price')
    
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2f}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(uniformtext_minsize=12, uniformtext_mode='hide')
    
    return fig.to_json()

def code_generation_llm(product: pd.DataFrame) -> str:

                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price',

    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Ensure data is in the right format
    product['unit_price'] = product['unit_price'].astype(float)
    
    # Create a bar plot for product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in the Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price'},
                 text='unit_price')

    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2f}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(yaxis_title='Unit Price (in $)', xaxis_title='Product Name')
    
    # Return plot in json format
    return fig.to_json()

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Creating a bar plot to show product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Products and Their Prices',

                 color='unit_price',
                 text='unit_price')

                      xaxis_title='Product Name',
                      showlegend=False)
    
    return fig.to_json()

import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Create a bar plot for products and their prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Products and Their Prices', 
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'})
    
    # Update layout for better readability
    fig.update_layout(xaxis_title='Product Name', 
                      yaxis_title='Unit Price ($)', 
                      yaxis=dict(tickprefix="$"),
                      template='plotly_white')
    
    return fig.to_json()

user_query: What are the products and their price in the store?
plot_code:
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Creating a bar plot for products and their prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Products and Their Prices',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'},
                 color='unit_price',
                 text='unit_price')
    
    # Update the layout for better readability
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(yaxis_title='Unit Price ($)', xaxis_title='Product Name', showlegend=False)

    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Create a bar plot for product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in the Store',
                 labels={'product_name':'Product Name', 'unit_price':'Unit Price ($)'},
                 text='unit_price')
    
    # Update traces to show the price on top of the bars
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text}', textposition='auto')
    
    # Update layout for better readability
    fig.update_layout(yaxis_title='Unit Price ($)', xaxis_title='Product Name')
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Create a bar plot for product prices
    fig = px.bar(product, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='unit_price', 
                 title='Product Prices in Store',
                 labels={'product_name': 'Product Name', 'unit_price': 'Unit Price ($)'},
                 text='unit_price')
    
    # Update the layout for better aesthetics
    fig.update_traces(texttemplate='%{text:.2f}', textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(uniformtext_minsize=8, uniformtext_mode='hide', xaxis_tickangle=-45)
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product: pd.DataFrame, sales_of_product: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    # Merge the datasets on product_id to combine product details with sales data
    merged_data = pd.merge(sales_of_product, product, on='product_id')

    # Group by product_name and sum the quantity sold
    sales_summary = merged_data.groupby('product_name').agg(total_quantity=('quantity', 'sum')).reset_index()

    # Create a bar plot
    fig = px.bar(sales_summary, x='product_name', y='total_quantity', 
                 title='Total Sales Quantity by Product', 
                 labels={'total_quantity': 'Total Quantity Sold', 'product_name': 'Product Name'},
                 color='total_quantity', 
                 template='plotly_white')

    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(sales_of_product):
    # Assume product DataFrame is also available as 'product'
    
    # Sample data for product DataFrame for demonstration
    product = pd.DataFrame({
        'product_id': [1, 2],
        'product_name': ['Google Pixel', 'SamSung Galaxy'],
        'unit_price': [800, 900]
    })
    
    # Merge the sales data with product information
    merged_data = pd.merge(sales_of_product, product, on='product_id')

    # Group by product and sum the quantity sold
    sales_summary = merged_data.groupby(['product_name'])['quantity'].sum().reset_index()

    # Create bar plot
    fig = px.bar(sales_summary, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='quantity', 
                 title='Total Product Sales', 
                 labels={'quantity':'Total Quantity Sold', 'product_name':'Product Name'},
                 color='product_name')

    # Return the plot in JSON format
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    total_products = product['product_id'].nunique()
    plot_data = pd.DataFrame({'Total Products': [total_products]})
    
    fig = px.bar(plot_data, x='Total Products', y=[total_products], title='Total Number of Products', labels={'y':'Number of Products'})
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_title: Sales Quantity of Products Over Time
user_query: Show sales of all three products as line chart
plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(sales_of_product):
    # Ensure sale_date is in datetime format
    sales_of_product['sale_date'] = pd.to_datetime(sales_of_product['sale_date'])
    
    # Group by sale_date and product_id to get the total sales quantity for each product
    sales_summary = sales_of_product.groupby(['sale_date', 'product_id']).sum().reset_index()
    
    # Create a line chart
    fig = px.line(sales_summary, 
                  x='sale_date', 
                  y='quantity', 
                  color='product_id', 
                  title='Sales Quantity of Products Over Time',
                  labels={'quantity': 'Quantity Sold', 'sale_date': 'Date', 'product_id': 'Product ID'})
    
    # Return the plot in json format
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(product):
    # Count the total number of products
    total_products = product['product_id'].nunique()

    # Create a bar plot for the total number of products
    fig = px.bar(x=['Total Products'], y=[total_products], 
                 title='Total Number of Products',
                 labels={'x': 'Product Categories', 'y': 'Count'},
                 text=[total_products],
                 color=['Total Products'])
    
    # Update layout for better readability
    fig.update_traces(textposition='outside')
    fig.update_layout(yaxis=dict(title='Count'), xaxis=dict(title='Product Categories'))
    
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(sales_of_product: pd.DataFrame, product: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    # Merge the sales data with the product data
    merged_data = pd.merge(sales_of_product, product, on='product_id')
    
    # Summarize sales quantity by product name
    sales_summary = merged_data.groupby('product_name')['quantity'].sum().reset_index()
    
    # Create bar plot
    fig = px.bar(sales_summary, 
                 x='product_name', 
                 y='quantity', 
                 title='Total Sales of Products', 
                 labels={'quantity': 'Total Quantity Sold', 'product_name': 'Product Name'},
                 template='plotly')
    
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(sales_of_product):
    # Convert sale_date from milliseconds to datetime
    sales_of_product['sale_date'] = pd.to_datetime(sales_of_product['sale_date'], unit='ms')
    
    # Group by sale_date and sum the quantities sold
    sales_summary = sales_of_product.groupby('sale_date', as_index=False)['quantity'].sum()
    
    # Create the line chart
    fig = px.line(sales_summary, x='sale_date', y='quantity', 
                  title='Sales Over Time',
                  labels={'sale_date': 'Sale Date', 'quantity': 'Quantity Sold'})
    
    return fig.to_json()

plot_code:
import pandas as pd
import plotly.graph_objects as go

def code_generation_llm(Stock_Cluster):
    # Convert the input data into a DataFrame
    df = pd.DataFrame(Stock_Cluster)
    
    # Convert the 'Date' column to datetime format
    df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], unit='ms')

    # Create the plot
    fig = go.Figure()
    
    # Add a trace for the closing prices
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=df['Date'], y=df['Close'], mode='lines+markers', name='Close Price'))

    # Add a trace for the opening prices
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=df['Date'], y=df['Open'], mode='lines+markers', name='Open Price'))

    # Update layout
    fig.update_layout(title='Stock Prices Over Time',
                      xaxis_title='Date',
                      yaxis_title='Price',
                      legend_title='Price Type',
                      template='plotly_white')

    # Return the plot as JSON
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.graph_objects as go

def code_generation_llm(Stock_Cluster):
    # Assuming Stock_Cluster is a DataFrame containing the stock data.
    
    # Calculate the difference between Close and Open prices
    Stock_Cluster['Difference'] = Stock_Cluster['Close'] - Stock_Cluster['Open']
    
    # Create the plot
    fig = go.Figure()
    
    fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=Stock_Cluster['Date'], 
                             y=Stock_Cluster['Difference'], 
                             mode='lines+markers', 
                             name='Close - Open'))
    
    fig.update_layout(title='Difference Between Close and Open Values',
                      xaxis_title='Date',
                      yaxis_title='Difference',
                      template='plotly_white')
    
    return fig.to_json()

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px

def code_generation_llm(googleplaystore):
    # Filter the dataset to remove instances where Rating differences are below zero
    filtered_data = googleplaystore[googleplaystore['Rating'] >= 0]
    
    # Create a bar plot to visualize the Ratings of each App
    fig = px.bar(filtered_data, 
                 x='App', 
                 y='Rating', 
                 title='App Ratings', 
                 labels={'App': 'Application', 'Rating': 'User Rating'},
                 color='Rating')
    
    # Update layout for better readability
    fig.update_layout(xaxis_title='Application',
                      yaxis_title='User Rating',
                      xaxis_tickangle=-45,
                      height=400)
    
    return fig.to_json()

import plotly.graph_objects as go
import pandas as pd

def code_generation_llm(Stock_Cluster: pd.DataFrame) -> str:
    # Ensure the 'Date' column is in datetime format
    Stock_Cluster['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(Stock_Cluster['Date'], unit='ms')
    
    # Create the candlestick plot
    fig = go.Figure(data=[go.Candlestick(x=Stock_Cluster['Date'],
                                          open=Stock_Cluster['Open'],
                                          high=Stock_Cluster['High'],
                                          low=Stock_Cluster['Low'],
                                          close=Stock_Cluster['Close'])])
    
    # Update layout
    fig.update_layout(title='Candlestick Plot of Stock Data',
                      xaxis_title='Date',
                      yaxis_title='Price',
                      xaxis_rangeslider_visible=False)

import pandas as pd
import plotly.express as px
import numpy as np

def code_generation_llm(Stock_Cluster):
    # Assuming Stock_Cluster is a DataFrame passed to this function
    df = Stock_Cluster.copy()

    # Convert Date column to datetime format
    df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Date'], unit='ms')

    # Calculate trendline using numpy's polyfit
    z = np.polyfit(df['Date'].astype(int) / 10**9, df['Close'], 1)  # Fit a line
    p = np.poly1d(z)  # Create a polynomial function

    # Create a new column for trendline values
    df['Trendline'] = p(df['Date'].astype(int) / 10**9)

    # Create the plot
    fig = px.line(df, x='Date', y='Close', title='Stock Closing Prices with Trendline')
    
    # Add trendline to the plot
    fig.add_scatter(x=df['Date'], y=df['Trendline'], mode='lines', name='Trendline', line=dict(dash='dash'))

    # Update layout for better readability
    fig.update_layout(xaxis_title='Date',
                      yaxis_title='Price',
                      legend_title='Legend',
                      template='plotly_white')

    return fig.to_json()
